This paper deals with a logical framework for reasoning about distributed knowledge and communication among agents, which is a topic that falls under the scope of several subfields of computer science. The use of temporal logic and model-checking techniques suggests that the paper is related to formal methods and verification, which are often associated with the cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) sub-category. The focus on distributed knowledge and communication also suggests connections to artificial intelligence (cs.AI), game theory (cs.GT), and multi-agent systems (cs.MA), which are all areas that deal with the interaction between agents and their environment. Finally, the use of games with imperfect information and partially observable objectives suggests a connection to decision theory and algorithmic game theory, which are often associated with the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. Overall, the most likely sub-categories for this paper are cs.LO, cs.AI, cs.GT, cs.DS, and cs.MA, in that order.
